✅ 1. Design User & Order Schema (Mongoose)

In real applications:

A User can have many Orders

An Order belongs to one User

That is a One-to-Many relationship

So we use:

User collection

Order collection

Reference using ObjectId

✅ User Schema
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema(
  {
    name: {
      type: String,
      required: true,
      trim: true
    },

    email: {
      type: String,
      required: true,
      unique: true,
      lowercase: true
    },

    password: {
      type: String,
      required: true,
      minlength: 6
    },

    role: {
      type: String,
      enum: ["user", "admin"],
      default: "user"
    }
  },
  { timestamps: true }
);

module.exports = mongoose.model("User", userSchema);

✅ Why this schema is good (Interview Points)

required ensures data integrity

unique prevents duplicate emails

enum limits role values

timestamps auto adds createdAt & updatedAt

✅ Order Schema
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const orderSchema = new mongoose.Schema(
  {
    userId: {
      type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId,
      ref: "User", // Reference User model
      required: true
    },

    items: [
      {
        productName: {
          type: String,
          required: true
        },

        quantity: {
          type: Number,
          required: true,
          min: 1
        },

        price: {
          type: Number,
          required: true
        }
      }
    ],

    totalAmount: {
      type: Number,
      required: true
    },

    status: {
      type: String,
      enum: ["pending", "paid", "shipped", "delivered"],
      default: "pending"
    }
  },
  { timestamps: true }
);

module.exports = mongoose.model("Order", orderSchema);

✅ Why Reference Instead of Embedding?

Because user may have thousands of orders → embedding would exceed size limits.

So we reference:

userId: ObjectId → User

✅ 2. Using populate() (Join in MongoDB)

MongoDB does not have joins like SQL.

Mongoose provides populate() to fetch referenced documents.

Example: Fetch Orders with User Details
const orders = await Order.find().populate("userId");

Output:
[
  {
    _id: "order123",
    totalAmount: 5000,
    userId: {
      _id: "user789",
      name: "Niroj",
      email: "niroj@gmail.com"
    }
  }
]


So populate replaces userId with full user object.

Populate Only Specific Fields
const orders = await Order.find().populate("userId", "name email");


Only returns:

name

email

Populate with Conditions
const orders = await Order.find({ status: "paid" })
  .populate("userId");

✅ 3. Indexing in MongoDB (Pros & Cons)

Indexing is one of the most asked interview topics.

✅ What is an Index?

An index is a data structure that improves query speed.

Without index:

MongoDB scans every document (collection scan)

With index:

MongoDB uses a shortcut (fast lookup)

Example
Query:
db.users.find({ email: "niroj@gmail.com" })


If email is indexed → fast search

Creating Index
db.users.createIndex({ email: 1 })


Or in schema:

email: {
  type: String,
  unique: true
}


(unique automatically creates index)

✅ Indexing Pros
1. Faster Reads (Search Queries)
User.findOne({ email })


Becomes extremely fast.

2. Faster Sorting
Order.find().sort({ createdAt: -1 })


If createdAt is indexed → fast sorting.

3. Faster Filtering
Order.find({ status: "pending" })

❌ Indexing Cons
1. Slower Writes

Every insert/update must also update index.

So:

Inserts slower

Updates slower

2. Extra Storage

Indexes take memory/disk space.

3. Too Many Indexes Reduce Performance

Bad example:

Indexing every field → wasteful

✅ Best Practice (Interview Answer)

👉 Index fields that are frequently used in:

Search (find)

Filtering (where)

Sorting (sort)

Joining (foreign keys)

Example:

email

userId

createdAt

